### Struct Methods

Methods are functions with a special receiver argument.

### Value Receiver

```go
type Rectangle struct {
    Width  float64
    Height float64
}

func (r Rectangle) Area() float64 {
    return r.Width * r.Height
}

func main() {
    rect := Rectangle{Width: 10, Height: 5}
    fmt.Println(rect.Area()) // 50
}
```

### Pointer Receiver

```go
func (r *Rectangle) Scale(factor float64) {
    r.Width *= factor
    r.Height *= factor
}

func main() {
    rect := Rectangle{Width: 10, Height: 5}
    rect.Scale(2)
    fmt.Println(rect.Width) // 20
}
```

### Value vs Pointer Receiver

| Aspect | Value Receiver | Pointer Receiver |
|--------|---------------|------------------|
| Modifies struct | No (copy) | Yes (original) |
| Performance | Copies struct | Passes pointer |
| Consistency | Read-only methods | All methods |

### When to Use Pointer Receiver

1. Method modifies the receiver
2. Struct is large (avoid copying)
3. Consistency - if any method needs pointer, use pointer for all

### Method on Non-Struct Types

Methods can be defined on any type in the same package:

```go
type MyInt int

func (m MyInt) IsPositive() bool {
    return m > 0
}

func main() {
    var n MyInt = 42
    fmt.Println(n.IsPositive()) // true
}
```

### Method Chaining

```go
type Builder struct {
    result string
}

func (b *Builder) Add(s string) *Builder {
    b.result += s
    return b
}

func (b *Builder) String() string {
    return b.result
}

// Usage
var b Builder
result := b.Add("Hello ").Add("World ").Add("!").String()
```

> **Key Point:** If any method needs a pointer receiver, use pointer receivers for all methods on that type. This provides consistent behavior.

codeExample:
package main

import "fmt"

type Counter struct {
    Value int
}

// Pointer receiver - modifies the counter
func (c *Counter) Increment() {
    c.Value++
}

// Value receiver - read only
func (c Counter) Display() string {
    return fmt.Sprintf("Count: %d", c.Value)
}

func main() {
    c := Counter{}
    c.Increment()
    c.Increment()
    fmt.Println(c.Display()) // Count: 2
}
